From 5e6320b1442239e69a5d08999f91ddaccdcd6033 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Volker Badziong <development@richtfest.tech>
Date: Tue, 21 Jul 2026 03:59:43 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 07/11] Stage per-server slice properties across server startup

A game server's load-time peak routinely dwarfs its steady working set --
world generation and asset streaming reach for everything at once -- so a
memory.high sized for the steady state throttles precisely the phase that can
least afford it.

That would merely be slow if floor and ceiling were independent, but they are
not. memory.min and memory.low only fend off reclaim driven from OUTSIDE a
cgroup, so reclaim a cgroup inflicts on itself -- by exceeding its own
memory.high, or its own memory.max -- ignores them entirely. A ceiling below
the load-time peak therefore evicts the server straight through its own floor,
and the damage is permanent: nothing faults those pages back except the
workload itself, one at a time. Operators are left with a server pinned well
under a floor that is configured, applied and completely effective.

Add a startup band: WINGS_CG_STARTUP_MEMORY_MIN/_LOW/_HIGH/_MAX and
docker.per_server_slices.startup_defaults, applied by OnBeforeStart -- the one
path that actually precedes a boot -- and replaced by the steady band once the
server is up. Only the memory band is staged; cpu/io weights are
work-conserving and cannot evict anything.

Environment.Create() deliberately keeps applying the steady band: it also runs
at Wings boot, for a newly created server and for an incoming transfer, none
of which start the server, and a startup band applied there would never be
replaced.

The transition reuses detection Wings already performs. The egg's startup
"done" matcher sets the running state, which reaches OnStateChange -- so the
trigger is per-egg configuration every game already carries, and no new
console parsing is introduced. A startup_grace timer (default 15m) bounds the
band for servers whose ready line never matches. Note that state-change events
are dispatched one goroutine each and OnStateChange re-reads current state, so
"starting" can be coalesced away; that only costs the timer, and a server that
never reaches "running" is safer holding the startup band anyway.

Applications are gated on the bands actually differing, so a node that
configures no startup band issues no extra systemd calls and arms no timers --
its behaviour is unchanged apart from the config file gaining the new keys.

Every application logs the slice it targets, the phase, what triggered it and
the properties applied, with sizes rendered in the units they were configured
with instead of raw byte counts:

  cgroups: ensured per-server slice  slice=wings-<32hex>.slice phase=startup
    reason="server starting" properties="MemoryMin=9G MemoryHigh=64G ..."

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
